===Civil War years===
In February, 1861, [[Abraham_Lincoln|Abraham Lincoln]] travelled through Camden Station in February 1861, on his way to [[Washington,_D.C.|Washington, D.C.]] to be inaugurated as [[President_of_the_United_States|President of the United States]].<ref name=Toomey>{{cite book |author=Scott Sumpter Sheads and Daniel Carroll Toomey |title=Baltimore During the Civil War |publisher=Toomey Press |location=Linthicum, Maryland |year=1997 |page=170 |lccn=97060687 }}</ref> News of the [[Battle_of_Fort_Sumter|Battle of Fort Sumter]], beginning the [[American_Civil_War|Civil War]], first reached Baltimore on April 12, 1861, at the B&O's Camden Station telegraph office.<ref name=Potter /> The following week, Union troops of the 6th Massachusetts Regiment travelling south on the B&O barricaded themselves at Camden Station when they were attacked by Confederate sympathizers in the [[Baltimore_riot_of_1861|Baltimore riot of 1861]].<ref name=Potter /> During the four-year conflict, the B&O's line between Baltimore and [[Washington,_D.C.|Washington, D.C.]] was the sole rail link between the Federal capitol and the North, resulting in a vital role for Camden Station as B&O's Baltimore terminal.<ref name=Stover>John F. Stover, ''History of the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad''. West Lafayette, Ind.: Purdue University Press, 1987 (ISBN 0-911198-81-4), pp. 172–176.</ref> Trainloads of wounded soldiers and [[Confederate_States_Army|Confederate]] [[Prisoner_of_war|POW]]s came through the station following the [[Battle_of_Antietam|Battle of Antietam]], {{convert|75|mi|km|0}} west of Baltimore on September 17, 1862.<ref name=Toomey /> President Lincoln changed trains at Camden Station on November 18, 1863 en route to [[Gettysburg,_Pennsylvania|Gettysburg, Pennsylvania]] to deliver the [[Gettysburg_Address|Gettysburg Address]].<ref name=Toomey /> Lincoln also used Camden Station on April 18, 1864 when he made an overnight visit to Baltimore for a speaking engagement. A year later, at 10 a.m. on April 21, 1865, the assassinated president's nine-car [[funeral_train|funeral train]] arrived at Camden Station, the first stop on its slow journey from Washington to [[Springfield,_Illinois|Springfield, Illinois]], via the B&O and the [[Northern_Central_Railway|Northern Central Railway]]'s Baltimore-[[Harrisburg,_Pennsylvania|Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]], line.<ref>{{cite book|last=Toomey|first=Daniel Carroll|title=The Civil War in Maryland|year=1983|url=https://archive.org/details/civilwarinmaryla0000toom|publisher=Toomey Press|location=Baltimore, Md.|isbn=0-9612670-0-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/civilwarinmaryla0000toom/page/152 152]}}</ref>

